BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
To solve, we first separate the variable terms and constant terms to different sides of the equation. Then we eliminate the variable term's coefficient.

[```\newcommand{\subtractright}[1]{{\highlight{{{}-#1}}}}\newcommand{\divideunder}[2]{\frac{#1}{{\highlight{{#2}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
7-3y\amp=-8\\
7-3y\subtractright{7}\amp=-8\subtractright{7}\\
-3y\amp=-15\\
\divideunder{-3y}{-3}\amp=\divideunder{-15}{-3}\\
y\amp=5
\end{aligned}
```]

Checking the solution [`y=5\text{:}`]

[```\newcommand{\substitute}[1]{{\color{blue}{{#1}}}}\newcommand{\confirm}[1]{\stackrel{\checkmark}{#1}}\newcommand{\wonder}[1]{\stackrel{\text{?}}{#1}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
7-3y\amp=-8\\
7-3(\substitute{5})\amp\wonder{=}-8\\
7-15\amp\confirm{=}-8
\end{aligned}
```]

So the solution to the equation [`7-3y=-8`] is [`5`] and the solution set is [`\{5\}\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

